cards.desc:
# Description

The Spring Framework is an application framework and inversion of control container for the Java platform. The framework's core features can be used by any Java application, but there are extensions for building web applications on top of the Java EE platform. Although the framework does not impose any specific programming model, it has become popular in the Java community as an alternative to, replacement for, or even addition to the Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) model. The Spring Framework is open source

More information: [https://spring.io/](https://spring.io/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Spring is the strategic choice of web framework for Java based API's and services.
cards.name: Spring

cards.desc:
# Description

Apache Maven is a software project management and comprehension tool. Based on the concept of a project object model (POM), Maven can manage a project's build, reporting and documentation from a central piece of information.

More information:

[maven.apache.org](https://maven.apache.org/)
[Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Maven)

# Status

Adopt: It is an industry and Ticketmaster standard for managing build processes.

# Accepted Use Cases

Managing build processes.
cards.name: Maven

cards.desc:
# Description
Flexible dashboarding application for time-series data.  http://grafana.org/
# Status
A very active Opensource project, supporting OpenTSDB plus some additional features.
# Accepted Use Cases
Potential replacement for Metrilyx (which is written in house and lacks a maintainer).  Currently no supported "centralised" instances, but possible to stand up standalone instances (particularly easy using their Docker container)
cards.name: Grafana

cards.desc:
# Description

Gitlab-CI provides test capabilities integrated directly into Github/Gitlab. This providese test pass visibility on the repo itself, as well as providing a much simpler integration for handling unit testing.

# Status

PROTOTYPE - https://contegixapp1.livenation.com/confluence/display/INPS/IPS+-+Gitlab+CI+prototype+for+IPS+dockerization

# Accepted Use Cases
cards.name: Gitlab-CI

cards.desc:
# Description

Mock Services are used to provide a real interface to conduct Unit and Integration Testing against. 

Mock Services are typically used to represent a 3rd party API in a unit testing environment because they support testing of edge cases and failure modes that the real API won't reliably produce.

# Accepted Use Cases

Mock Services should be used to aid with unit testing (and specifically when using BDD) to validate behaviour with known responses.
cards.name: Mock services

cards.desc:
# Description

Robust generalized object/blob store. Latencies higher than disk access, but highly scalable throughput and very economical storage costs.
cards.name: AWS S3

cards.desc:
# Description

Fluentd is an open source data collector, which lets you unify the data collection and consumption for a better use and understanding of data.
cards.name: Fluentd

cards.desc:
# Description

WireMock is a flexible library for stubbing and mocking web services. Unlike general purpose mocking tools it works by creating an actual HTTP server that your code under test can connect to as it would a real web service.

It supports HTTP response stubbing, request verification, proxy/intercept, record/playback of stubs and fault injection, and can be used from within a unit test or deployed into a test environment.

Although it’s written in Java, there’s also a JSON API so you can use it with pretty much any language out there.

For more information: [http://wiremock.org/](http://wiremock.org/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Use for standing up mock services to aid with unit testing against API's.
cards.name: WireMock

cards.desc:
# Description

Cucumber is a software tool that computer programmers use for testing other software. It runs automated acceptance tests written in a behaviour-driven development (BDD) style. 

Cucumber is written in the Ruby programming language.[6][7] Cucumber projects are available for other platforms beyond Ruby. Some use Ruby Cucumber with a bridge into the target language (e.g. cuke4php and cuke4lua). Others use the Gherkin parser but implement everything else in the target language.[8] 

Cucumber allows the execution of feature documentation written in business-facing text. Capybara, which is a part of the Cucumber testing framework, is an example of a web based test automation software.

For more information: [https://cucumber.io/](https://cucumber.io/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Default choice for BDD testing.
cards.name: Cucumber

cards.desc:
# Description

Effectively PHP's standard framework and component library. Well designed, thoroughly documented and widely used outside TM.

https://symfony.com/doc/current/index.html

# Status

Adopt wherever possible in PHP-based projects

# Use Cases

MFOL's AccountManager provides a good example of when to use these components:

- Symfony/Config
- Symfony/Console
- Symfony/DependencyInjection
- Symfony/Event-dispatcher
- Symfony/HttpFoundation
- Symfony/HttpKernel
- Symfony/Process
- Symfony/Routing
- Symfony/Stopwatch
- Symfony/Validator
- Symfony/Yaml

MFOL replaces parts of it's in-house built framework with Symfony's standalone components one by one to slowly strangle the legacy framework and reduce the code base
cards.name: Symfony

cards.desc:
# Description

Java is a general-purpose computer programming language that is concurrent, class-based, object-oriented,[13] and specifically designed to have as few implementation dependencies as possible. It is intended to let application developers "write once, run anywhere" (WORA),[14] meaning that compiled Java code can run on all platforms that support Java without the need for recompilation.[15] Java applications are typically compiled to bytecode that can run on any Java virtual machine (JVM) regardless of computer architecture.

For more information:
https://www.java.com/
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_%28programming_language%29

Use the latest version of java and jvm, currently version 8, as soon as possible  in order to be up to date with security and other upgrades. 

# Status

Adopt: Industry and Ticketmaster standard for creating cross platform web applications and services.

# Accepted Use Cases

Preferred language for creating backend web applications and services.
cards.name: Java

cards.desc:
# Description

Apache Tomcat, often referred to as Tomcat, is an open-source web server developed by the Apache Software Foundation (ASF). Tomcat implements several Java EE specifications including Java Servlet, JavaServer Pages (JSP), Java EL, and WebSocket, and provides a "pure Java" HTTP web server environment in which Java code can run.

For more information:
https://tomcat.apache.org/
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Tomcat

Use the latest version of Tomcat, currently version 8, as soon as possible in order to be up to date with security and other upgrades. 

# Status

Adopt:This is the preferred Java Servlet container within Ticketmaster.

# Accepted Use Cases

Java Servlet container.
cards.name: Tomcat

cards.desc:
# Description

Ubiquitous RDBMS which is fast, has ACID properties and can easily be scaled-out for read-queries. Newer 5.7 versions also possess clustering abilities.  

# Status

The most used database in the world and inside TM. If you are targeting AWS, consider Aurora and/or Amazon RDS.

# Accepted Use Cases

Use as a data store for canonical data, OLTP processing, backing store for queuing systems, etc.
cards.name: MySQL

cards.desc:
# Description

Jenkins is a build and deployment tool used widely within TM.It supports a wide variety of plugins to aid in most automation and build scenarios.

More information: [https://jenkins.io/](https://jenkins.io/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Jenkins should be the default choice for build server in all applications.
cards.name: Jenkins

cards.desc:
# Description

SonarQube (formerly Sonar) is an open source platform for continuous inspection of code quality.

For more information:
http://www.sonarqube.org/
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SonarQube

# Status

Adopt: Standard tool within Ticketmaster for code quality.

# Accepted Use Cases

Use as a tool for continuous inspection of code quality.
cards.name: SonarQube

cards.desc:
# Description

Swagger is a simple yet powerful representation of your RESTful API. Swagger is available in almost every modern programming language and deployment environment. With a Swagger-enabled API, you get interactive documentation, client SDK generation and discoverability.

For more information: [http://swagger.io/](http://swagger.io/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Swagger should be a default choice for providing self-documenting endpoints on RESTful API's.
cards.name: Swagger

cards.desc:
# Description
> A time-series oriented application, layered on top of HBase, to store and serve massive amounts of data without losing granularity.  http://opentsdb.net/

# Status
> Deployed and supported internally for Production and Non-Production metrics.  https://contegixapp1.livenation.com/confluence/display/SYAR/OpenTSDB+Integration

# Accepted Use Cases
> Time-series, value-based metric data that needs long retention and high resolution.  Not suitable for textual data, or data with high cardinality dimensions.
cards.name: OpenTSDB

cards.desc:
# Description

Chef is used to streamline the task of configuring and maintaining a company's servers.  It uses a pure-Ruby, domain-specific language (DSL) for writing system configuration "recipes".
For more information: [https://www.chef.io/chef/](https://www.chef.io/chef/)

# Status
Early stages of deployment on the Windows Infrastructure, with Linux integration coming in Q2 2016.

# Accepted Use Cases
Chef is the strategic choice for infrastructure automation on both Windows and Linux OS's.
cards.name: Chef

cards.desc:
###Description

####.Net
The Microsoft .Net framework provide a comprehensive programming model for building a wide range of application types. Programs written for .NET Framework execute in the context of a managed environment - in effect a virtual machine - known as Common Language Runtime (CLR). The CLR provides services such as security, memory management, and exception handling. In addition to the CLR the .Net Framework provides a set of standard class libraries that implement a number of common programming functions such as reading and writing files etc.

The .Net framework has wide adoption throughout industry.

####C-Sharp
C# is a type-safe object-oriented programming language that enables developers to build a variety of secure and robust applications that run on the .NET platform. The language has its roots in the C family of languages and will be immediately familiar to C, C++, and Java programmers.

Along with the .Net Framework the C# language has wide adoption throughout industry. 

For more information: 
[https://www.microsoft.com/net/default.aspx](https://www.microsoft.com/net/default.aspx)
[https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/kx37x362.aspx](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/kx37x362.aspx)

###Status

This is in the ADOPT column as this is widely used and an industry standard.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

Both the .Net Framework and the C# programming language are suitable for use in a wide range of application scenarios including back-end service, desktop and web application development.
cards.name: .NET/C#

cards.desc:
###Description

ASP.NET MVC is Microsoft's implementation of the MVC design pattern for web application development. It provides a patterns-based way to build dynamic websites that enables a clean separation of concerns and that gives you full control over markup. ASP.NET MVC includes many features that enable fast, TDD-friendly development for creating sophisticated applications that use the latest web standards.

For more information: 
http://www.asp.net/mvc

###Status

This is in the ADOPT column as this is widely used and an industry standard.

### Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use in web application development.
cards.name: ASP.net MVC

cards.desc:
# Description
WebPageTest is an industry standard performance testing tool. Should be combined with sitespeed.io to give relevant performance metrics.

For more information: 
[http://www.webpagetest.org/](http://www.webpagetest.org/)

# Status
This is in the ADOPT column as this is used successfully within Resale and other areas.

# Currently Accepted Use Cases
This is correct for use with web applications.
cards.name: WebPageTest

cards.desc:
# Description
JMeter can be used as a unit test tool for JDBC database connections,FTP, LDAP, Webservices, JMS, HTTP, generic TCP connections and OS Native processes. JMeter can also be configured as a monitor, although this is typically considered an ad hoc solution in lieu of advanced monitoring solutions. It can be used for some functional testing as well.

For more information: 
[http://jmeter.apache.org/](http://jmeter.apache.org/)

# Status
This is in the ADOPT column as this is open source and widely used.

# Currently Accepted Use Cases
This is correct for use with any application, but primarily web applications.
cards.name: JMeter

cards.desc:
###Description

Gatling is an open-source load testing framework based on Scala, Akka and Netty.

The software is designed to be used as a load testing tool for analyzing and measuring the performance of a variety of services, with a focus on web applications.

The Project's aims include;

- High performance
- Ready-to-present HTML reports
- Scenario recorder and developer-friendly DSL

For more information: 
[http://gatling.io/#/](http://gatling.io/#/)

###Status

This is in the ADOPT column as this is open source and widely used.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use with any application, but primarily web applications.
cards.name: Gatling

cards.desc:
# Description

The Reliable, High Performance TCP/HTTP Load Balancer. http://www.haproxy.org/

# Status

Deployed in a couple of small places internally. Pretty straightforward to configure, rock solid. 

# Accepted Use Cases

Use in any on-premise cluster with no netscaler where a quick load-balancing/failover solution is needed, or inside AWS for almost all your load-balacing needs.
cards.name: HAProxy

cards.desc:
# Description

Google Page Speed Insights measures the performance of a page for mobile devices and desktop devices. It fetches the url twice, once with a mobile user-agent, and once with a desktop-user agent.

The PageSpeed Score ranges from 0 to 100 points. A higher score is better and a score of 85 or above indicates that the page is performing well. Please note that PageSpeed Insights is being continually improved and so the score will change as we add new rules or improve our analysis.

For more information: 
[https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/insights/](https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/insights/)

# Status

This is in the ADOPT column as this is widely used and an industry standard.

# Currently Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use with any publicly facing web application.
cards.name: PageSpeed Insights

cards.desc:
###Description

YellowLab tools offers free performance testing and device emulation for measuring web page performance.

For more information: 
[http://yellowlab.tools/](http://yellowlab.tools/)

###Status

This is in the ADOPT column as this is widely used and an industry standard.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use with any publicly facing web application.
cards.name: YellowLab Tools

cards.desc: RDS offers significant reduction of management overhead of databases and is strongly recommended if its feature set meets your needs. Also refer to the individual RDBMS engine in the Tech Radar as there are many different types of RDS service.
cards.name: AWS RDS

cards.desc:
# Description

Javascript runtime environment running on the V8 engine

# Use cases

Standard use cases are: 

- Build tools for Front End pipelines
- Rendering engines (in the context of BEFFE applications)
cards.name: Node.js

cards.desc:
# Description

Javascript View library for building performant, consistent web applications

Use with [Redux](http://redux.js.org/) for managing complex state

# Status

Adopt: React is in use across multiple B2B and B2C platforms.

# Accepted Use Cases

React is suitable for any web application, but its main strength is found

- In interfaces that require complex state management between distinct parts of the UI (e.g. a page containing a ticket listing and a basket that need to be kept in sync
- Where the possibility exists to server-side render the view via Node (e.g. BEFFE-style architectures that connect a view renderer to a distinct back-end)
cards.name: React

cards.desc:
# Description

Low level / system oriented programming language.

# Status

Used by MNX core ticketing engine and MNX client B2B tools. 

# Accepted use cases

Core ticketing inventory tasks where performance is priority - seat searches - creating orders - printer drivers.
While actively used for specific projects, particularly involving the host and Microflex core ticketing engine, should not be selected for general purpose cases as the talent pool is getting scarce.
 .
cards.name: C++

cards.desc:
###Description

> Domain-Driven Design is a technique to model and maintain software by coupling the implementation with a continually evolving model of the requirements. The key idea is that significant generalisation of the implementation often leads to significantly more work and tends to create more complexity than often required. The technique helps (and requires) significant collaboration between technical and domain experts to refine each model representing a business domain problem/requirement. 

###Status

> This is in the CONSULT column as knowledge and experience within Ticketmaster is still growing, support is required for those teams who are looking to adopt the practice.
cards.name: Domain-driven design

cards.desc:
# Description

> Solr is highly reliable, scalable and fault tolerant, providing distributed indexing, replication and load-balanced querying, automated failover and recovery, centralized configuration and more. Solr powers the search and navigation features of many of the world's largest internet sites.

> For more information: [http://lucene.apache.org/solr/](http://lucene.apache.org/solr/)

# Accepted Use Cases

> Use for any full-text search or search needs.
cards.name: SOLR

cards.desc:
#Description

Ghostery is a proprietary freeware privacy-related browser extension for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Microsoft Internet Explorer, Opera, and Apple Safari owned by the advertising and privacy technology company Ghostery, Inc. (formerly Evidon). 

It enables its users to easily detect and control HTTP cookies, which are objects embedded in a web page, invisible to the user, which allow collection of the user's browsing habits. Ghostery also has a privacy team that creates profiles of page elements and companies for educational purposes.

For more information: 
[https://www.ghostery.com/](https://www.ghostery.com/)

#Status

This is in the CONSULT column as this is used within Resale, but needs assessing in other areas.

#Currently Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use with any publicly facing web application.
cards.name: Ghostery

cards.desc:
ImmutableJS,  
Immutable Java: http://immutables.github.io/immutable.html
cards.name: Immutable Data

# Description

Main drivers for tech choices are language features, and a goal to be completely non-blocking. Scala has been widely adopted across the industry and this provides TM with an opportunity to determine its applicability within engineering.

# Use case

Grapevine, a service for real-time reserves with external inventory, is using Scala. Includes use of SBT, Play Framework and Akka.
cards.name: Scala

cards.desc:
# Description
Go (often referred to as golang) is an open source programming language. Designed primarily for systems programming, it is a compiled, statically typed language in the tradition of Algol and C, with garbage collection, limited structural typing, memory safety features and CSP-style concurrent programming features added.

For more information: https://golang.org/

# Status
This is in the Consult column as this is used successfully within the industry but internal experience is limited.

# Currently Accepted Use Cases
This is correct for use for prototyping new web applications, micro services and infrastructure tooling. Adoption to be checked with the Enterprise Architecture team.
cards.name: Go

cards.desc:

Synthetic performance monitoring tool to show real-time statistics.

For more information: 
[https://speedcurve.com/](https://speedcurve.com/)

This is in the Consult column as this is used successfully within Resale, however is paid for and therefore should be used sparingly.

mPulse is a Real User Monitoring (RUM) tool to show performance statistics in real time.

This is correct for use with web applications already utilising SOASTA.

# Description

Docker is an open-source project that automates the deployment of applications inside software containers, by providing an additional layer of abstraction and automation of operating-system-level virtualization on the Operating System. Containers provide a lightweight way of virtualising components and moving like for like infrastructure between environments.

For more information: [https://www.docker.com/](https://www.docker.com/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Docker is a strategic choice going forward, however the accepted implementation is yet to be define and as such EA should be consulted if Docker is a choice.
cards.name: Docker

cards.desc:
# Description

Talend is an ETL and Data Management platform that provides capabilities to manage data integrations and governance.

For more information: [https://www.talend.com/](https://www.talend.com/)

# Accepted Use Cases

Talend provides the capability to manage ETL processes, through custom services or using open source software such as Apache Storm. This should be used to manage ETL loads only.
cards.name: Talend

cards.desc:
# Description

> Provides a structure for routing and mediation in services, utilising common Enterprise Integration Patterns through a standard DSL.

> For more information: [http://camel.apache.org/](http://camel.apache.org/)

> A good article explaining when to use Camel : [https://dzone.com/articles/open-source-integration-apache](https://dzone.com/articles/open-source-integration-apache)

AWS Lambda is a serverless execution engine in AWS.

Languages supported include NodeJS, Java, and Python

https://aws.amazon.com/lambda/
cards.name: AWS Lambda

Usually used for notifications/alerts/triggers and is the preferred way to identify when something has changed with AWS. If you are doing something high throughput or need guaranteed ordering, consider Kinesis instead.

Performance monitoring tool for web applications.

###Status

This is in the CONSULT column as this is widely used, however it is licensed and needs to be used sparingly.

This is correct for use with any publicly facing web application.

Very common language and used extensively via Wordpress.

This is in the CONSULT column as PHP is not a strategic language, however we do recommend its use, in particular with Wordpress.

For use with existing PHP based applications, or where Wordpress is selected for use.

Distil provides bot and scraping protection from front-end websites.

[http://www.distilnetworks.com/](http://www.distilnetworks.com/)

This is in the CONSULT column as this is used successfully within Resale but needs evaluation before use in other areas.

Apiary provides API documenting and prototyping abilities.

This is in the CONSULT column as this is used within International, however the use of an API documentation tool is not standardised yet.

cards.desc:
# Description

Currently our default provider for CDN, global load-balancing and DNS edge acceleration

# Accepted Use Cases

- to provide DNS-based global load-balancing between clusters (Akamai GTM or Global Traffic Management)
- as a content delivery network, caching static content at edge locations to reduce bandwidth requirements from our data centres and improve site responsiveness (Akamai DSA or Dynamic Site Accelerator)
- DNS traffic offload and acceleration: all our primary domains are slaved to Akamai and domain delegations are pointed directly to Akamai's server (Akamai FastDNS)
- Full site proxying (Akamai SiteShield) is used by TMOL and Ticketweb T4 but no products developed by TM International and is costly, as such we don't currently consider it in the "ADOPT" category

# Notes

Performs very well but nobody seems to know how much it costs other than "a lot" - this aspect is a concern and far from transparent.
cards.name: Akamai

cards.desc:
# Description

Drupal is one of the most popular open source content management systems worldwide, powering about 2.2% of all websites. It is the leading CMS for enterprise-level, high-traffic sites. Other than a CMS, it is also a high-level content management framework for creating web apps, built on top of PHP and Symfony.

Notable organisations using Drupal for their main site (as opposed to just a blog site) are the Rio 2016 Olympics, The White House, The Economist, Royal Mail, Eurostar, University of Cambridge.

# Status

Consult: Widely used across Ticketmaster, but continued use should be assessed against other options.

# Accepted Use Cases

* Rapid prototyping of high-level web apps (especially if CMS or user-generated content functions are required), as there are more than 35,000 plug-and-play modules providing different functionalities such as authentication, permissions management, creating API endpoints. This allows development to focus on the business logic.
Examples: Forum, document/info sharing site, ticket listing

* Custom integration with existing systems, as Drupal is also a flexible, modular content management framework.
Examples: ClientHub (integrates with TMOne OpenSocial framework for Single Sign On, Salesforce API for support/CRM functions, BrightCove for playing video, Wordpress feeds for content aggregation)
 
* API/Headless/Decoupled CMS - where Drupal works as the backend/API for a frontend framework. Out of the box, Drupal 8 (latest version) is a decoupled CMS, see http://blog.openlucius.com/en/blog/headless-drupal-why-how-restful-api-drupal
cards.name: Drupal

cards.desc: Excellent NoSQL document store however 100% specific to AWS so could be adopted but with caution due to lock-in
cards.name: AWS DynamoDB

cards.desc: AWS' DNS service. Used internally and strongly recommended for all services running in AWS. Not recommended at present for public domains but only due to lack of evaluation and process around how best to manage these.
cards.name: AWS Route53

cards.desc:
# Description

Real-time distributed computation / data processing framework. Provides reliable processing for unbounded streams of data.
http://storm.apache.org/

# Status

PROTOTYPE

# Accepted Use Cases

ETL, Realtime Analytics, Online Machine Learning
cards.name: Apache Storm

cards.desc:
# Description

A data store based on Lucene that is based around inverted indexes of documents. Largely used to enable full-text search of large volumes of data, Elastisearch is fully multi-tenant and horizontally scalable when configured correctly.

# Accepted Use Cases

Not usually used as a source of truth for business data but rather as a way to search the full corpus of data and then lookup those records against a canonical store.
cards.name: Elasticsearch

cards.desc:
###Description

Redis is an open source (BSD licensed), in-memory data structure store, used as database, cache and message broker.It supports data structures such as strings, hashes, lists, sets, sorted sets with range queries, bitmaps, hyperloglogs and geospatial indexes with radius queries. Redis has built-in replication, Lua scripting, LRU eviction, transactions and different levels of on-disk persistence, and provides high availability via Redis Sentinel and automatic partitioning with Redis Cluster.

For more information: 
[http://redis.io/](http://redis.io/)

###Status

This is in the PROTOTYPE column as this is not currently widely used within Ticketmaster and is currently scehduled for a POC with the Ticketmaster Pro team.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

The currently accepted use case is for Caching and maintaining session state.
cards.name: Redis

cards.desc:
# Description
Horizontally scalable pub-sub messing. Use the 0.8.x or later Kafka, as prior versions are not compatible and had design flaws. Queue holds a fixed window of the most recent messages (usually set large enough for at least a day's worth of messages), with clients responsible for tracking their own consumption.
For more information: http://kafka.apache.org/

# Status
Deployed and in use in several areas.  Not particularly widely understood/supported.  Almost identical to AWS Kinesis.

# Accepted Use Cases
Should be thought of as more of a distributed commit log than a fully-fledged message bus.  Appropriate for forming the backbone of an on-prem data pipeline.
cards.name: Kafka

cards.desc:
# Description

Comprises two separate AWS services equivalent to Apache Kafka: 
Provides high throughput, reliable, partially ordered, horizontally scalable pub-sub style messaging. As with Kafka, the queues (streams) are stateless; clients are responsible for managing and persisting their checkpoint in the queue. 
Is generally more limited than Kafka, but nicely integrated with other AWS services and of course requires no operational support.

Kinesis Streams:
https://aws.amazon.com/kinesis/streams/
The Kinesis Streams service allows you to develop bespoke client applications that consume from the stream

Kinesis Firehose:
https://aws.amazon.com/kinesis/firehose/
The Firehose service is a more managed service that allows the user to configure AWS-managed propagation onwards into S3, Redshift and ElasticSearch. However, no bespoke client applications can access the data stored here

# Status

PROTOTYPE

# Accepted Use Cases
cards.name: AWS Kinesis

cards.desc:
# Description

A .NET (Mono) based cross-platform framework to write mobile apps. Requires a local runtime that can make distributed binaries larger than completely native applications, but has comparable to native runtime performance.

Allows applications to be structured/built in a way that business services, view models, repositories etc are all shared between different mobile platforms but views can be customised per platform - to give a native feel to the application.

Does also support 'Xamarin Forms' which is a one size fits all UI framework - but we do not recommend the use of this as it has too many corner cases.

# Accepted Use Cases

* In use for building complex B2B applications (IAC scanners initially) where there is a significant quantity of client side logic that needs to be consistent across platforms.

* NOT acceptable for B2C applications currently due to the inflated download size of applications.
cards.name: Xamarin

cards.desc:
###Description

When two independently developed services are collaborating, changes to the supplier’s API can cause failures for all its consumers. Consuming services usually cannot test against live suppliers since such tests are slow and brittle, so it’s best to use Test stubs/mocks, leading to the danger that the test stubs/mocks get out of sync with the real supplier service. Consumer teams can protect themselves from these failures by using integration contract tests – tests that compare actual service responses with test values. While such contract tests are valuable, they are even more useful when consuming services provide these tests to the supplier, who is then able to run all their consumers’ contract tests to determine if changes are likely to cause problems for any consumer – i.e. consumer-driven contracts.

###Status

This is in the WATCH column as this is not currently widely used within Ticketmaster. Where there is a potential for POCing this technique, it will a member from the EA team can support getting this into the Prototype column and to help define the boundaries for the POC with a means to feedback the learnings to the business.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

API services
cards.name: Consumer-driven contracts

# Description

etcd is a distributed, consistent key-value store for shared configuration and service discovery, with a focus on being:

 * Simple: curl'able user-facing API (HTTP+JSON)
 * Secure: optional SSL client cert authentication
 * Fast: benchmarked 1000s of writes/s per instance
 * Reliable: properly distributed using Raft

https://github.com/coreos/etcd

# Status 

It has been prototyped in Cloudsys, contact Guillaume for details.

# Accepted Use Cases

etc.d seems to avoid some of Zookeeper's rough edges, and is lighter weight. The initial implementation had some issues, but the 2.0 implementation is really well done. Handy presentation: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6tjawXZ71E

etcd appears to have picked up a lot of Zookeeper's momentum, with newer cloud/distributed computing open source projects adopting it (Kubernetes, Cloud Foundry, Mesos & Mesosphere, etc.). Zookeeper still has more adoption in the distributed Java world, but my best guess is that in a couple of years etcd will be the default coordination/service discovery store of choice.
cards.name: etcd

cards.desc:
# Description

Hyperbahn enables service discovery and routing for large-scale systems comprised of many microservices. Distributed, fault tolerant, and highly available, it lets one service find and communicate with others simply and reliably without having to know where those services run.

Hyperbahn is an overlay network of routers designed to support the TChannel RPC protocol. Hyperbahn itself is based on Ringpop. Its router nodes dynamically converge and gossip known services onto a consistent hash ring topology, forming a mesh of services that can send requests to each other without human intervention or knowledge of specific ports and addresses.
(https://github.com/uber/hyperbahn)[https://github.com/uber/hyperbahn]

# Status

Watch: No real reason to use this yet until our own Microservice usage matures, but one to watch.

# Accepted Use Cases

Only for large scale Microservices architecture.
cards.name: HyperBahn

# Description
Rust is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm, compiled programming language sponsored by Mozilla Research. It is designed to be a "safe, concurrent, practical language", supporting functional, and imperative-procedural paradigms.

For more information: https://www.rust-lang.org/

# Status

cards.name: Rust

cards.desc:
# Description

A highly efficient method of serializing data structures into relatively compact binary representations. Can be used both for storage (generally temporary cache) or for communication between internal services where network efficiency is of the utmost concern.

Serialization can be defined either in code using the generic suite of protobuf client libraries (which exist for most programming platforms), or through an IDL which can then be compiled into client/server stubs.

Can be made forward and backwards compatible with some effort, and the largest caveat is the lack of object inheritance which has to be rolled by hand by using object composition.

# Accepted Use Cases

* Currently not actually in use anywhere

* Candidate for exposing high-volume information externally (e.g. ISM real-time availability feed) or for internal communication between services.

* Should not be used without consultation for any publicly facing services.
cards.name: Protocol Buffers

###Description

CPPSDK is a “modern C++, async. multiplatform API that supports the consumption of REST services” with a focus on JSON response documents. There is currently no support for SOAP. The CPPSDK contains support for programming with tasks based on C++11 features, json parsing, async. streams, uri helper and a http_client across  windows, linux, OS X, Android, Windows Phone and iOS.

Each of the TM Intl mobile projects involves heavy consumption of API services - the cppsdk may provide an opportunity to create a common codebase (service client) that can be shared across the main mobile platforms. This is now probably more relevant to us since it is likely that native mobile development may be be delegated to an agency.

For more information: 
[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WvaxcicwIss](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WvaxcicwIss)
[http://casablanca.codeplex.com](http://casablanca.codeplex.com)

###Status

This is in the Watch column as we need to complete an assessment before we can ascertain whether or not we should adopt this. This should be assessed alongside React Native as a full stack option.

###Currently Accepted Use Cases

This is correct for use within native mobile applications only.
cards.name: C++ REST SDK

cards.desc:
###Description

VoltDB is a scale-out NewSQL relational database that supports SQL access from within pre-compiled Java stored procedures. The unit of transaction is the stored procedure, which is Java interspersed with SQL. VoltDB relies on horizontal partitioning down to the individual hardware thread to scale, k-safety (synchronous replication) to provide high availability, and a combination of continuous snapshots and command logging for durability (crash recovery).

For more information: 
[https://voltdb.com/](https://voltdb.com/)

###Status

This is in the Watch column as this is currently not used, but may be useful in multiple applications.
cards.name: VoltDb

lists.name: ADOPT - technologies and practices that have proved their merit for general use
CONSULT - widespread industry acceptance but limited internal experience; consider adopting in your project
PROTOTYPE / REVIEW - technologies and practices that are being prototyped and scheduled to be prototyped.
WATCH - have industry buzz but may not be ready for prime time.
DEPRECATE - problematic or of limited applicability; where reasonable, avoid and even replace.
